Field Label: STUDY DESCRIPTION

First, I want you to know that whether or not you participate in the study is entirely up to you, and if you decide not to participate, it will not affect your care in any way.

 

The purpose of this research study is to learn about a possible treatment for temporomandibular disorder (TMD) pain. This study will test the use of Photobiomodulation (PBM), which is a combination of low-level cold laser therapy and Light-emitting Diodes. PBM, or light therapy, has been used to treat muscle pain and other pain conditions for over 30 years. This study will test if this type of treatment is helpful for people suffering with TMD pain. For the PBM treatment, you will be randomly assigned (like the flip of a coin) to receive either real or placebo light therapy. Placebo light therapy is similar to real light, however, the light does not have the same active effects.

 

Participation in this study will consist of eleven visits. Ten of these visits will be over a 6-7-week period, and the last visit will be scheduled 6 months after the 10th visit. There will also be follow-up phone assessments 1 and 3 months after the 10th visit.

We are looking for volunteers to take part in this study. If you choose to participate, you will be asked to come to our research clinic at the University of Florida for 11 visits. The entire study would last approximately 7-8 months . The first visit is a screening session that will take up to 3 hours. The other visits will last between 1 and 2½ hours.

 

During the study, you will participate in clinical exams and sensory tests, provide a blood samples and complete several questionnaires about your health and pain at each visit.  Additionally, you will be asked to keep a brief daily symptom diary for the duration of the study.

 

You will receive up to $500 for completing the whole study.

Section Header:
Unblinding Procedure:
In the event of an emergency, when a patient or medical care provider contacts us to inquire about the type of treatment a patient is receiving as part of the study, the following protocol will be implemented:

1. The concerned patient will be redirected to engage in a conversation with the Lab Manager.

2. The Lab Manager will then initiate contact with the statistician to ascertain the patient's assigned treatment.

3. Subsequently, the Lab manager will communicate this treatment information to the patient or medical provider.

4. It's important to note that the Lab Manager will not divulge the treatment assignment to any other individuals involved in the study.

5. The Lab Manager will meticulously record this information in a securely encrypted electronic Case Report Form (eCRF) and promptly report it to the Medical Monitor.

Instructions: Your first task is a Sustained Vowel Phonation Task. We are looking at your ability to control your pitch and volume and your vocal quality as well. So, I want you to take a deep breath and then sustain the vowel "E" for as long as you can without taking another breath.

(Start recording)

Instructions: For this task, I need you to say: "pataca, pataca, pataca, pataca, pataca, pataca," as many times as you can for 15 seconds. I want to observe your rate, your rhythm, and the precision of your articulation.

(Start recording and stop recording at each attempt)

Section Header:
6. Muscle and TMJ Pain with Palpation (1Kg)

Now I am going to apply pressure to different areas of your head and face, and I will ask you about pain, familiar pain, and familiar headache. [Pause]

 

I will prompt you with the words "pain", "familiar pain", and "familiar headache."

 

As we continue on in the examination, familiar pain refers to pain that you have experienced in the last 30 days in the same area that I am palpating.

Familiar headache is Pain "similar" or "like" the headache you have experienced in the temple area(s) in the last 30 days.

 

[Patient can be asked to clench the teeth together in order to identify the borders of the muscles.]

Please relax your jaw.

 


TMJ Lateral Pole Palpation (0.5 Kg)

Open slightly, and move your jaw forward and then move it back to its normal position with your teeth slightly apart.

Pain?

Is this pain familiar to you?  


Around the Lateral Pole (1 Kg)
Open slightly, and move your jaw forward a little bit and keep it there.

Pain?

Is this pain familiar to you?

Field Label:
1.1            Participant Inclusion Criteria

To be eligible to participate in this study, an individual must meet all of the following criteria (See Table 1 for inclusion criteria by session):

  • Male or female, aged 18 years and older
  • Meets the CATI pre-screening criteria during pre-screening visit [participant-reported facial pain for at least 3 months and an average pain intensity rating for the week preceding CATI of ≥30 on a numerical rating scale (NRS, 0-100)].
  • Willing to provide signed and dated informed consent
  • Willing to to comply with all study procedures and to be available for the duration of the study
  • Meets diagnostic criteria for TMD (Masticatory Muscle disorder, 1 A: Myalgia) during Visit 0
  • Completes a minimum of 4 of 7 daily symptom diary (DSD) entries prior to Visit 1 (Randomization visit), and the weekly average pain score on this DSD is ≥30 of 100

1.2            Participant Exclusion Criteria

An individual who meets any of the following criteria will be excluded from participation in this study:

  • Active rheumatologic disease
  • Has a medical condition, laboratory finding, or physical exam finding (e.g., renal failure or dialysis, uncontrolled diabetes mellitus, hyperthyroidism, fibromyalgia, or uncontrolled seizures) that precludes participation as determined by the investigator
  • Initiated occlusal appliance therapy within 30 days prior to CATI
  • Initiated non-pharmacologic therapy, such as acupuncture, biofeedback, and/or TENS within 30 days prior to CATI
  • Is in active orthodontic treatment
  • Received any injection therapy (e.g., tender or trigger point injections, steroid injections) for the management of pain within 14 days prior to the CATI
  • Has a history of facial trauma or orofacial surgery within 6 weeks prior to CATI
  • Has a history of psychiatric hospitalization within one year prior to CATI
  • Currently pregnant or lactating
  • Has a known hypersensitivity to laser therapy
  • Currently being treated with chemotherapy or radiation therapy
  • Is undergoing treatment with another investigational drug or treatment initiated within 30 days prior to the Screening and Baseline Visit
  • Initiated a new daily prescribed or over-the counter medication for the management of pain within 30 days prior to Screening and Baseline Visit.
  • Anything that would place the individual at increased risk or preclude the individual's full compliance with or completion of the study as determined by the investigator
